    'sub.radiesse.doctors.title': "Doctors Who Perform Radiesse",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.title': "Radiesse — Frequently Asked Questions",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.1.q': "What is Radiesse made of?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.1.a': "Radiesse is made of calcium hydroxyapatite (CaHA) microspheres suspended in a gel carrier. CaHA is a mineral naturally found in human bone, which makes it very biocompatible.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.2.q': "Is Radiesse a filler or a biostimulator?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.2.a': "Both. The gel gives immediate volume like a filler, and the CaHA microspheres stimulate your own collagen and elastin over the following months — that dual action is what makes it distinctive.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.3.q': "How long does Radiesse last?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.3.a': "Results typically last 12 to 18 months, depending on the area treated, the amount used and your metabolism. A top-up session maintains the effect.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.4.q': "When will I see results?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.4.a': "You see lift and contour immediately from the gel. The collagen-building effect develops gradually over the following weeks and months, so the result matures over time.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.5.q': "Is Radiesse painful?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.5.a': "Numbing cream or local anaesthetic is used, and a version containing lidocaine is available. Most people describe mild pressure rather than pain.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.6.q': "Can Radiesse be dissolved like other fillers?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.6.a': "No. Unlike hyaluronic acid fillers, Radiesse cannot be dissolved with hyaluronidase — it is gradually absorbed by the body instead. This is exactly why it should only be injected by an experienced doctor.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.7.q': "Can Radiesse be used in the lips?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.7.a': "No. Radiesse is not used for lip augmentation because of the risk of nodules. A hyaluronic acid filler is the appropriate choice for lips.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.8.q': "What is hyperdilute Radiesse?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.8.a': "It is Radiesse diluted and placed more superficially to improve skin firmness and crepiness rather than add volume — often used for the neck, décolleté, arms and hands.",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.9.q': "How much does Radiesse cost?",
    'sub.radiesse.faq.9.a': "Pricing depends on how many syringes your plan needs and the areas treated. You'll receive a clear quote after your assessment — book a free consultation to start.",
    'sub.radiesse.review.1.name': "Rania M.",
